[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(13) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Children of Belial.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The very same expression is used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 20:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : “Deliver us the men, the children of Belial, that are among you.” This is the first place where the expression “sons of Belial” occurs, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 19:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is the second. It is generally explained by modern scholars as “worthlessness.” Rashi curiously makes it “destroyers of the yoke” (of Jehovah).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Deuteronomy 13:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Certain men, children of Belial — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "So the most profligate and worthless are called in Scripture. The expression properly signifies persons ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "without yoke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "lawless, and rebellious, that will suffer no restraint, that neither fear God nor reverence man. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Are gone out from you — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Have separated themselves from you in point of religion, and carry themselves stubbornly and presumptuously herein.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
