  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 13.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Men, the children of Belial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sons of worthlessness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", utterly worthless persons. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Beli ya'al",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (a compound of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בְלִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עָל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to ascend, to have worth, to profit) means primarily that which is low, hence worthlessness, naughtiness, wickedness. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 15:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Belial is rendered in the Authorized Version as an adjective, \"wicked,\" and also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 18:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it is rendered by \"ungodly men.\" Most commonly it is treated as a proper name. But in all places the proper meaning of the word might be retained. The Hebrews described an object, of which any quality was predominantly characteristic, as the son of that quality. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Are gone out from among you",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; have gone forth from the midst of you, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". have risen up among yourselves. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Withdraw",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The verb here is the same as that rendered by \"thrust,\" in vers. 5 and 10. It conveys the idea of drawing away with some degree of force, not mere easy seduction, but impulsion by strong persuasion. Deuteronomy 13:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The third case is that of a town that had been led away to idolatry. \"If thou shalt hear in one of thy cities.\" בּאחת, not de una, of one, which שׁמע with בּ never can mean, and does not mean even in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 26:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The thought is not that they would hear in one city about another, as though one city had the oversight over another; but there is an inversion in the sentence, \"if thou hear, that in one of thy cities...worthless men have risen up, and led the inhabitants astray to serve strange gods.\" לאמר introduces the substance of what is heard, which follows in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". יצא merely signifies to rise up, to go forth. מקּרבּך, out of the midst of the people. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]